<div type="definition">
<p>TEMPERATURE RESEMBLING that of FIRE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. Probably the most general word referrring to objective high temperature or heat is rè 熱 (ant. lěng 冷 "cold").</p>
<p>2. Wēn 溫 (ant. liáng 涼 "cool") is mild heat.</p>
<p>3. Nuǎn 暖 (ant. liáng 涼 "cool") is very mild heat.</p>
<p>4. Yán 炎 is extreme heat.</p>
<p>5. Shǔ 暑 (ant. hán 寒 "cold") refers to perceived heat, which often relates to humidity in the air as well as objective temperature.</p>
<p>6. Xū 煦 and hé 和 refer to temperate, comfortable, and warm temperatures or climates.</p>
        </div>
